## SCSS for ODS Component Parts

**When styling ODS components, use @ods skill to understand component structure and available parts for styling.**

### ODS Component Styling

```scss
// ✅ GOOD: Style ODS component parts using ::part()
ods-text.font-bold::part(text) {
  font-weight: bold;
}

ods-text.text-critical::part(text) {
  color: var(--ods-color-critical-500);
}

ods-text.disabled::part(text) {
  opacity: 0.6;
}
```

### Custom SCSS

```scss
// ✅ GOOD: Custom styles in SCSS when needed
.custom-component {
  position: relative;
  min-height: 90vh;
  
  .nested-element {
    z-index: -1;
    position: absolute;
  }
}
```

### SCSS File Structure

```scss
// ✅ GOOD: Main SCSS file structure
@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;
@import '@ovhcloud/ods-themes/default';

html {
  font-family: var(--ods-font-family-default);
}

// ODS component customizations
ods-text.custom-class::part(text) {
  /* styles */
}
```

## Styling Best Practices

### When to Use Tailwind vs SCSS

- **Tailwind**: Primary method for all styling
- **SCSS**: 
  - ODS component parts (`::part()` selectors)
  - Complex custom styles that are hard to express with utilities
  - Global styles in `index.scss`

### ODS Theme Integration

- Always use `var(--ods-color-*)` for colors
- Use `var(--ods-font-family-default)` for fonts
- Use `var(--ods-size-*)` for sizing when available
- Import ODS theme: `@import '@ovhcloud/ods-themes/default';`

### Responsive Patterns

- Mobile-first approach
- Use breakpoints: `sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`, `xl:`
- Common pattern: `className="base-class md:desktop-class"`

### Conditional Styling

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD: Use clsx for conditional classes
import clsx from 'clsx';

<div
  className={clsx('base-class', {
    'active-class': isActive,
    'error-class': hasError,
    'disabled-class': isDisabled,
  })}
>
  Content
</div>
```
